commitResults.messageTitle: Refactor edit_s command: remove role editing and update CCA behavior
commitResults.messageBody:
- Update the usage and implementation of EditStudentCommand to accept only
  [n/NAME] [p/PHONE] [e/EMAIL] [a/ADDRESS] and [c/CCA_NAME].
- Remove any handling of the role field; edit_s no longer edits a student's role.
- Modify CCA parsing in EditStudentCommandParser to support a single CCA name.
- Add an overloaded ParserUtil.parseCcaInformation(String) to handle single input
  and assign a default role.
- Allow clearing of a students CCAs by providing an empty c/ prefix.

commitResults.messageTitle: Refactor: Encapsulate CCA adding logic in Person class
commitResults.messageBody:
Introduced Person.addCca(CcaInformation) to handle the creation
of a new Person instance with an added CCA. Updated AddCcaToStudentCommand
to use this method instead of manually constructing the new Person.

This improves encapsulation by moving the responsibility of creating
the modified Person state into the Person class itself, reducing
coupling with the command.

commitResults.messageTitle: Refactor: Remove redundant try-catch in AddCcaToStudentCommand
commitResults.messageBody:
Removed the try-catch block handling IllegalArgumentException around
the call to `model.setPerson`.

This catch was primarily intended to handle potential CCA validation
errors. However, checks earlier in the command's `execute` method
already ensure that the added CCA exists in the model's CCA list,
making the validation error during `setPerson` highly unlikely in this
context and the catch block unnecessary.

Replaced try-catch around `model.setPerson` with an explicit call
to `model.isValidPersonCcas(editedPerson)` before the set operation.

This validates CCA integrity upfront and allows the command to throw
the correct CommandException directly, improving control flow and
error handling clarity. Removes reliance on catching exceptions
from `setPerson` for standard CCA validation.
